![vending machines in japan](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2018/09/IMG_20170622_203029-800x533.jpg)

Vending machines in Honmachi entertainment district, Tsuruga, Japan. Photo by
Nevin Thompson.

Japanese vending machines have long been famous for selling the most curious
things, like flowers, umbrellas, and ties. But even with [one vending machine
for every 23 people](https://www.japan-guide.com/e/e2010.html) and [annual
sales that exceed $60 billion,](https://www.businessinsider.com/why-so-many-
vending-machines-in-japan-2017-1) one can still be surprised at what comes out
of their take-out port.

User [senegirl](https://matome.naver.jp/profile/senegirls) on Japanese
curation site [Naver Matome](https://matome.naver.jp/odai/2153589684205086001)
tells the story of three unique food vending machines found in three separate
cities that have captived Twitter.

> 日本初?!らしいけど…  
>  pizzaが焼きたてで買える自動販売機(笑)  
>  中でおじさんが焼いてるわけではなさそうでした。
> [pic.twitter.com/MnNCiDpDZH](https://t.co/MnNCiDpDZH)
>
> — ケロちゃん@グラブル初心者 (@Lee_sakura1210) [September 1,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/Lee_sakura1210/status/1035877647329312768?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> A first in Japan? Seems that way… It's a fresh-baked pizza vending Machine!
> (ha ha) I bet there's an old guy inside making them.

In the city of Hiroshima, residents have been abuzz over the appearance of a
pizza vending machine located near [local
hangout](http://nlab.itmedia.co.jp/nl/articles/1808/06/news105.html) TSUTAYA,
part of a national chain of bookstores in Japan. The vending machine serves up
two kinds of pizza:
[margherita](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pizza_Margherita) (basil,
mozzarella cheese, and tomato sauce) for about US$ 10 and four-cheese for
about US$ 13 with a cooking time of just three minutes. TSUTAYA's parent
company, which is behind the vending machines, hopes to eventually have other
such machines at bookstores across Japan.

In the meantime, locals are pleasantly surprised by just how tasty machine-
baked pizza can be.

